thoughts.a: The input and output grids are drastically different sizes. Input grid is large and contains a green color background with a bunch of objects inside of partial bounding boxes, of a variety of colors. Usually with input and output grids that are such different sizes, there is some selection rule that needs to be determined from the input grid so that we know what to put in the output grid. We notice immediately that the output contains yellow and green, and that the yellow shape in the output grid is the exact shape as one of the shapes in the input grid. we can see that each of the interior shapes can fit into a 3x3 grid, So presumably any one of them can be selected to be put into the output grid. What is special about the yellow sheep? We note that the colors of all the different candidate objects are different from one another, and also are different from the partial bounding box that surrounds those shapes. With the exception of one such object, which is the yellow object. For the yellow object, the partial bounding box that surrounds it is also yellow, the same color. Thus the hypothesis is the following. Input grid will be a large input grid of mostly some background color, in this case green. It will be a variety of objects encased in partial bounding boxes. Each of these colored objects can fit into a 3x3 grid. To construct the output grid, we need to identify which of these objects has the same color as its partial bounding box that is surrounding it. That object is thus selected as the output grid, copying over exactly as it is, including the background color where necessary.
thoughts.b: Input and output grids are drastically different sizes again. Input Grid has an aqua background this time, and contains variety of shapes that are encased by partial bounding boxes. We notice that all the shapes of different colors in the interior can fit inside of a 2x2 grid. According to the hypothesis, we need to identify which shape is the same color as the exterior partial bounding box that is surrounding that shape. In this case, all of the partial bounding boxes are blue, which means we need to find the whose color is blue. After identifying this shape, we need to copy it exactly as is into the output grid, including the background color aqua where necessary. Note that the output grid should be a 2x2 shape this time because all of the differnet interior objects can fit into a 2x2 grid. Because the output grid is this blue shape with one aqua background color, the hypothesis holds, with a slight modification that the shapes could potentially be any size, we just need to deduce it from the shapes present in the input grid.
thoughts.c: The input grid is once again a very large grid with a Yellow background color. The input grid contains four instances of a partial bounding box with an interior shape of a variety of different colors. According to the hypothesis, we need to first identify common size that these shapes can fit into. Each one of these shapes can fit into a five column wide and four row tall grid, Therefore, the output grid should be four rows tall and five columns wide. According to the hypothesis, we need to select the interior shape whose color matches the exterior partial bounding box that surrounds that shape. In this case, that shape is the red object. Thus we copy over into the output grid this red object along with the yellow color background that fills in the rest of the output grid. Because we once again have another case. of a slightly different size output grid shape, our slight change about needing to deduce the common size is strengthened. Thus the hypothesis holds.
thoughts.d: We apply the hypothesis here. Input grid is a large input grid with a yellow color background. There are six total partial bounding boxes of a variety of different colors. Each partial bounding box contains inside of them an object of some shape. According to the hypothesis, we need to identify the common size of all of these shapes. We notice that each one can fit into a 3x3 grid, So that should be the size of our output grid. According to the hypothesis, next we need to select the appropriate internal shape to copy over into the output grid. We do this selection by identifying the interior object whose color is the same as the partial bounding box that surrounds it. In this case, the red interior object matches the red partial bounding box that surrounds it, so we select this red object to be copied over as is to the output grid, along with any yellow background tiles that fill in the rest of the 3x3 output grid.
thoughts.e: We apply the hypothesis here. input grid is a large input grid with a blue color background. There are seven total partial bounding boxes of a variety of different colors. Each partial bounding box contains inside of them an object of some shape. According to the hypothesis, we need to identify the common size of all of these interior shapes. Upon inspection, we noticed that each one can fit into a 3x3 grid, and thus the output grid should be a 3x3 tile grid. According to the hypothesis, next, we need to select the appropriate internal shape to copy over into the output grid. We do this selection by identifying the interior object whose color is the same as the partial bounding box that surrounds it. In this case, looking at each of the seven instances, the purple interior object matches the purple partial bounding box that surrounds it. Thus we select this purple object to be copied over as is to the output grid along with any blue background tiles that fill in the rest of the 3x3 output grid.
